President
fields.description: The current President of Country X was a vocal opposition leader during the post-independence rule of the first President. He is a veteran of difficult political battles, having served time in prison under the former regime. No radical ideologue, he has however used ethnicity as a political tool in the past when pragmatically viewed as beneficial to maintaining power. His Kunai-Wia coalition party does have a vocal minority wing dedicated to xenophobic discourse, and they have attempted to use the economic downturn for a power grab within the party. The President has defined the opposition as 'terrorist', highlighting their tactics as an attempt to reject the legitimacy of his government.

fields.name: FirstWorldEnvoy
fields.description: The Deputy Chief of Mission has 12 years experience in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, and has been in Country X for three years. Serving first as a political officer in the Embassy charged with monitoring and reporting on the ongoing political instability in Country X, the envoy's facility with local languages and mastery of the political milieu led to her recent promotion as chief advisor to the Ambassador. In this capacity, the DCOM utilizes all domestic and regional assets, including intelligence, to collect information relevant to formulating her capital's policy in Country X. Since her country is the former colonial ruler in Country X, and long-time patron of the first President's regime, there is a complicated history and undercurrent of mistrust between her state and citizens of Country X. Since the outbreak of violence, the DCOM has been closely monitoring illegal weapons flows, the training of paramilitary forces, and violence directed toward civil society. She has been charged with providing conflict prevention recommendations to the Ambassador as well as policy feedback to her capital. The killing of 35 youths in the capital during the post-election violence had a profound effect, alerting her to the potential for the conflict to move from a political dispute to violence exhibiting a communal character.

fields.name: SubRegionalRep
fields.description: Country X has been a member of a sub-regional economic community for 13 years. Unlike many regional and sub-regional organizations, Country X's has a strong security apparatus as part of the organization's charter. The sub-regional organization has gone so far as to intervene with force in violent conflicts in the region, with member states providing their military assets for 'stabilization'. Recently, the sub-regional body has proposed a conflict early warning mechanism to be adopted and integrated into the fabric of the organization. A sub-regional representative has been in Country X for 6 months taxed with transforming 'lessons gathered' from previous conflicts in the region, into 'lessons learned' and applied in Country X. This process has been very slow due to logistical challenges for the sub-regional such as a lack of budget, lack of colleagues trained in conflict early warning, and local hostility to the sub-regional organization's presence and mandate. The representative is skilled in negotiation and mediation, as well as the tenants of conflict transformation and peace building. She/He was born in a neighboring country and is also very experienced in conflict assessment.

fields.name: OppositionLeadership
fields.description: The leader of the opposition, an ethnic Delp, communicated indirectly with commanders of the rural insurgency. He had been accused by the ruling party of having prior knowledge of insurgent attacks on government targets, with hard-liners in the governing party accusing the opposition leader of coordinating the attacks. The opposition leader is a skilled politician, having been part of the ruling elite for over a decade prior to the upheavals following the first President's death. When the first President's nephew fled the country following the attempted coup, the opposition leader stayed in the capital and maintained dialogue with the new President, eventually arranging a cessation of urban political violence. The opposition leader's position between the insurgency and the ruling government makes him an important figure but his political aspirations remain unclear. He is alternately viewed as a peacemaker by some, and guerrilla sympathizer by others. The ability to influence the insurgency to meet his political ends has been noted by third-party observers.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Negotiations

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Regime Change

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value: Conflicted parties decide to engage in negotiations. The President's decision to negotiate alters international perceptions of the conflict. Levels of violence decrease in the short term. Extremists in the President's party view negotiation as anathema, seeking to derail the possible peace process by increasing inflammatory rhetoric. Weapons flow remains steady. The negotiation process allows the conflicted parties time to plot their strategy while the President considers the prudence of conducting presidential elections in the near future. The International community, including the Western Envoy's capital and sub-regional organization, makes it clear that they favor a transitional government that leads to elections.  A network of civil society representatives in Country X have mobilized during the violence following the Presidential elections, and are actively encouraging dialogue between local, regional, and national actors.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Elections - Sanctions

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
The announcement of elections by the President had an immediate positive impact on levels of violence associated with the counter-insurgency. Violence decreased in the short term. The economy took a small hit due to the imposition of targeted sanctions by the international community. The sanctions were designed in part to coerce opposing groups to the bargaining table.

The leader of the opposition movement welcomed the announcement publicly, but deep skepticism and mistrust have resulted in a steady flow of weapons, despite sanctions, as opposition and hard-line elements of the ruling elite have begun to stockpile weapons as a hedge against an unfavorable outcome to the proposed election.

Although the President’s refusal to publicly acknowledge the leaders of the insurgency has deepened cleavages at the communal level in Country X, his government’s willingness to engage in quiet diplomacy with insurgent leaders through the mediation of the First World Envoy has begun to build confidence in the process among elites.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Elections - Peacebuilding

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
The President’s decision to go forward with elections has increased the political rhetoric between various groups within the country as electioneering is in full swing.

The quality of discourse among the key civil society members and local officials has improved dramatically in the few months since the First World Envoy instituted community conflict mitigation efforts.

Political extremists have taken note of this and are not supportive of these efforts, as discourse at the grassroots level has begun the shift away from Identity-based politics, and started to address issues of accountability from the political elite.

Levels of violence associated with the counterinsurgency are steady as opposition leaders maintain pressure in the run-up to elections.

The economy takes a small hit due to uncertainties surrounding the upcoming election. Military elite are closely monitoring the election process to calculate their position in a new government.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Sub-Regional Mediation

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value: The President call for Sub-regional Mediation has effectively removed the Western Envoy from the peace process.  The sub-regional organization's mediation effort adds legitimacy to the peace process and serves to acknowledge the growing threat that Country X's instability poses to neighboring states.  The Chairman of the Sub-regional organization, a long-ruling President and statesman in the sub-region begins mediation efforts between the warring parties.  Envoys are sent to his capital while the conflict continues in Country X.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Cancel Elections - COIN

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
The President’s decision to cancel the elections and choose violent counter-insurgency has created a tenuous position for him in the capital. The insurgency has responded with increased violence and is now pressuring state monopoly over violence in multiple regions of the country. Extremist elements in the ruling regime calculate that assassinating the opposition leadership in the capital will cripple the insurgency, and must be followed with full-scale genocide against the Delp to 'purify' the state following years of perceived Kunai-Wia marginalization. The spiraling violence and increased insecurity caused by the insurgency have caused moderates within the ruling regime to be silenced by extremist voices. Weapons are widely distributed to civilian supporters of the insurgency. The government has readied youth militias and paramilitaries in coordination with state security forces.

The President must decide between appeasing the extremists within his party by instituting a genocidal 'final solution', making a last ditch effort at negotiation with the Delp insurgency, or calling for international intervention under the auspices of the Responsibility to Protect.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Violence - Insurgency

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
Increase in insurgent violence has nullified Presidentail elections. The insurgency has created a tenuous position for the President in the capital. His government has responded with increased violence and is now in danger of relinquishing state monopoly over violence in multiple regions of the country.

Extremist elements in the ruling regime calculate that assassinating the opposition leadership in the capital will cripple the insurgency, and must be followed with full-scale genocide against the Delp to secure their position, as well as 'purify' the state following years of Kunai-Wia marginalization. The spiraling violence and increased insecurity caused by the insurgency have led moderates within the ruling regime to be silenced by extremist voices.

Weapons are widely distributed to civilian supporters of the insurgency. The government has readied youth militias and paramilitaries in coordination with state security forces.

The President must decide between appeasing the extremists within his party by instituting a genocidal 'final solution', making a last ditch effort at ceasefire negotiations with the Delp insurgency, or calling for international intervention under the auspices of the Responsibility to Protect.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Negotiation - Sanctions

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value: Conflicted parties decide to engage in negotiations. The President's decision to negotiate alters international perceptions of the conflict. Levels of violence decrease in the short term. Extremists in the President's party view negotiation as anathema, seeking to derail possible peace process by increasing inflammatory rhetoric. Weapons flow remains steady. The negotiation process allows the conflicted parties time to plot their strategy while weighing the feasibility of conducting presidential elections in the coming months. The International community, including the Western Envoy's capital and sub-regional organization make it clear that they favor a path that leads to elections, specifically the naming of a transitional government. The Western envoy's decision to recommend sanctions was taken into consideration by the capital, but deemed too drastic by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs at this stage of the conflict. However, economic and military sanctions remain policy options if negotiations break down. The President of Country X, already suspicious of the Western Envoy, has been alerted to her recommendation to the capital.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Violence - Sanctions

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value: The First World Envoy's decision to recommend sanctions against the warring parties has limited the military capabilities of both the government and the insurgency, despite the Government's decision to increase the violence of the counter-insurgency. The decision of the international community to impose sanctions has hardened the ruling regimes stance vis-a-vis a negotiated settlement. The envoy's sympathy toward the insurgency, has led to the President discounting the envoy as a neutral party. The government’s renewed refusal to speak to insurgent leaders has deepened cleavages at the communal level in Country X.  Both sides are seeking to subvert sanctions to arm themselves for an expansion of the war.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Violence - Sanctions

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
The President’s decision to choose violent counterinsurgency has created a tenuous position for him in the capital. The insurgency has responded with increased violence and is now pressuring state monopoly over violence in multiple regions of the country.

Extremist elements in the ruling regime calculate that assassinating the opposition leadership in the capital will cripple the insurgency, and must be followed with full-scale genocide against the Delp to secure their position, as well as 'purify' the state following years of Kunai-Wia marginalization. The spiraling violence and increased insecurity caused by the insurgency have led moderates within the ruling regime to be silenced by extremist voices.

Weapons are widely distributed to civilian supporters of the insurgency, despite efforts by the international community to stem the flow to government and non-state actors through the imposition of targeted sanctions. The government has readied youth militias and paramilitaries in coordination with state security forces.

The President must decide between appeasing the extremists within his party by instituting a genocidal 'final solution', making a last ditch effort at ceasefire negotiations with the Delp insurgency, or calling for international intervention under the auspices of the Responsibility to Protect.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Support Insurgents

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value: The Western Envoy's decision to support the insurgency diplomatically and materially has greatly damaged domestic and international confidence in the prospects for peace. The President and his advisors use the decision to inflame nationalist rhetoric. The insurgency - as well as any opposition party - is painted as a proxy of neo-colonial aspirations in the affairs of Country X. The Western Envoy's decision has led to covert transfers of arms to the insurgents through a bordering country with strong ties to the former regime, as well as the former colonial power. This increase in arms has led to an increase in violence through the insurgency. This support has hardened the ruling regime's stance as it now discounts the envoy as a neutral party. The government’s renewed refusal to communicate with the leaders of the insurgency has deepened cleavages at the communal level in Country X.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Cancel Elections - Negotiate

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value: The President cancels upcoming elections due to the real threat posed by the opposition at the polls. He calculates that an open election would be too risky for the regime. The President’s decision to cancel the elections and seek negotiations - possibly for a transitional government that protects his interest in power - has created a tenuous position for him in the capital. The insurgency has responded with increased violence and is now pressuring state monopoly over violence in multiple regions of the country. The spiraling violence and increased insecurity caused by the insurgency have caused moderates within the ruling regime to be silenced by extremist voices. Weapons are widely dispersed. The President must decide between appeasing the extremists within his party by instituting a genocidal 'final solution', making a last ditch effort at negotiation and powersharing with the Delp insurgency, or calling for international intervention under the auspices of the Responsibility to Protect.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Negotiations - Ceasefire

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value: President calls for ceasefire and engages in official peace negotiations with leadership of insurgency to pull back from spiraling violence and lay framework for powersharing.  Violence decreases sharply as government troops halt counter-insurgency activities and allow free movement of displaced peoples.  A combination of sustained international pressure, as well as punishment inflicted by the insurgency, convinced the president to save his regime and avoid an international intervention or military defeat.  His position is still tenuous, but the downturn in violence has allowed him more freedom to calculate his position going forward.  Extremist elements in his government are waiting for an opportunity to enact their extermination plan.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: R2P (imposed under element 3)

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
The International Community responds to the government’s violent intransigence by deploying a multinational protection force in coordination with the sub-regional security mechanism.

Military violence increases in the short term, while violence against civilians decreases dramatically.

Overall levels of violence decrease greatly.

IDP flows are reduced as international peacekeepers subsequently deploy throughout Country X.

The sub-regional rep and first world envoy coordinate UN and regional efforts to engage moderate government and insurgent leaders in talks to bring about peaceful resolution to the conflict.

Extremists in the President’s party are outraged by the international intervention, marginalized by the subsequent peace talk efforts, and continue to plot the 'final solution' to the Delp question.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Elections - Insurgency

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
The announcement of elections by the President had an immediate positive impact on several of the variables including prestige and international awareness. The leader of the opposition movement welcomed the announcement publicly, but deep skepticism and mistrust have led to an increase in the flow of weapons as opposition and hard-line elements of the ruling elite have begun stockpiling weapons as a hedge against an unfavorable outcome to the proposed election. Levels of violence increased due to an upsurge in insurgent violence. The economy received a small boost as the international community decided against the imposition of sanctions - targeted or otherwise.

Although the President’s refusal to publicly acknowledge the leaders of the insurgency has deepened cleavages at the communal level in Country X, his government’s willingness to engage in quiet diplomacy with opposition and insurgent leaders has begun to build confidence in the process among elites.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Ethnic Expulsion

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value: President decides to address insurgency, as well as opposition threat to his monopoly over power through violent expulsion of ethnic Delp from the capital and surrounding areas. A program of 'ethnic expulsion' is commenced by the regime, and facilitated by paramilitary groups under the guidance of regime hardliners and state security forces - namely the Presidential Guard. Large numbers of Delp civilians are forced out of the capital and surrounding territory. The insurgency responds by moving to seize territory in the periphery of Country X in which Delp populations are vulnerable, in an attempt to secure defensible enclaves.  Levels of violence increase as political discourse disintegrates.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Violence - Insurgency

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
The increase in the violence of the insurgency had an immediate negative impact on several of the variables:

Levels of violence associated with insurgency increased in the short term, and the economy took a hit as the international community imposed sanctions – targeted, yet still negatively affecting the general population.

Insurgent attacks on government and now civilian targets increased. The flow of weapons increases due to an increasing security dilemma by perceived by conflicted parties. The President must decide how to address insurgent violence, as well as opposition threat to his monopoly over power, through negotiations or other measures including violent expulsion of ethnic Delp from the capital and surrounding areas.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Violence - COIN

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
The increase in the violence of the President’s counter-insurgency had an immediate negative impact on several of the variables:

Levels of violence associated with COIN increased in the short term, and the economy took a hit.

The leader of the opposition movement instructed the insurgent leaders to increase attacks on government and now civilian targets. The flow of weapons is now unabated as all sides stockpile weapons due to an increased security dilemma. The government’s refusal to speak to the leaders of the insurgency has deepened cleavages at the communal level in Country X. Both sides are preparing for an expansion of the war.

The Government believes it can defeat the insurgency with superior military force.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Elections - Disputed

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value: Presidential elections are conducted and deemed a success by the ruling regime.  However, the opposition's refusal to stand for elections has furthered the political crisis in Country X.  Economy is improving due to increased political stability. Country X is still deeply impoverished but inequality is decreasing slowly due to new government’s inclusive policies. Community Conflict Mitigation efforts have strengthened dormant peace building networks throughout Country X. Civil society and local officials are taking the lead at the grassroots level, demanding accountability from the political elite.  Violence is greatly diminished. The flow of weapons drops markedly as border integrity is reasserted. Extremist elements are marginalized through public education efforts and improved monitoring of the political discourse.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Genocide

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
Government commences genocide against the Delp.

The government’s official position is that full-scale counterinsurgency is underway. Delp civilians are targeted in all areas of the country. Delp elite are summarily executed in the capital.

Delp insurgents in the periphery begin to target Kunai and Wia civilians.

Massive refugee flows out of Country X.

Economy is devastated as commerce is brought to a stand-still.

The sub-regional rep and first world envoy scramble to convince their constituencies to authorize military intervention.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: R2P (requested under element 2)

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
The International Community responds to the government’s request for internsational assisatnxe to protect civilians of Country X by deploying peacekeepers.

Delp insurgents in the periphery are separated from government troops and attacks against civilians decrease dramatically.

Levels of violence decrease greatly.

IDP flows are reduced as international peacekeepers deploy throughout Country X.

The sub-regional rep and first world envoy coordinate UN and regional efforts to engage the government and insurgent leaders in talks to bring about peaceful resolution to the conflict.

Extremists in the President’s party are outraged by the international intervention and continue to plot the 'final solution' to the Delp question.

fields.name: Short name
fields.value: Violence - COIN

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
The President’s decision to choose violent counterinsurgency has created a tenuous position for him in the capital. The insurgency has responded with increased violence and is now pressuring state monopoly over violence in multiple regions of the country.

Extremist elements in the ruling regime calculate that assassinating the opposition leadership in the capital will cripple the insurgency, and must be followed with full-scale genocide against the Delp to secure their position, as well as 'purify' the state following years of Kunai-Wia marginalization. The spiraling violence and increased insecurity caused by the insurgency have led moderates within the ruling regime to be silenced by extremist voices.

Weapons are widely distributed to civilian supporters of the insurgency. The government has readied youth militias and paramilitaries in coordination with state security forces.

The President must decide between appeasing the extremists within his party by instituting a genocidal 'final solution', making a last ditch effort at ceasefire negotiations with the Delp insurgency, or calling for international intervention under the auspices of the Responsibility to Protect.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Elections

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
The announcement of elections by the President had an immediate positive impact on several of the variables:

Levels of violence associated with the counter-insurgency decreased in the short term, and the economy received a small boost as the international community decided against the imposition of sanctions - targeted or otherwise.

The leader of the opposition movement welcomed the announcement publicly, but deep skepticism and mistrust have led to an increase in the flow of weapons as opposition and hard-line elements of the ruling elite have begun to stockpile weapons as a hedge against an unfavorable outcome to the proposed election.

Although the President’s refusal to publicly acknowledge the leaders of the insurgency has deepened cleavages at the communal level in Country X, his government’s willingness to engage in quiet diplomacy with insurgent leaders has begun to build confidence in the process among elites.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Elections (powersharing)

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value: Presidential elections are deemed a success and all parties accept the outcome.  A coalition government is formed and conflict moves from the street back into government house. Security sector reform becomes a central theme for stabilization of Country X. Depoliticization of the military, in particular, becomes a joint initiative of the new government. Economy is improving due to increased political stability. Country X is still deeply impoverished but inequality is decreasing slowly due to new government’s inclusive policies. Community Conflict Mitigation efforts have strengthened dormant peace building networks throughout Country X. Civil society and local officials are taking the lead at the grassroots level, demanding accountability from the political elite.  Violence is greatly diminished. The flow of weapons drops markedly as border integrity is reasserted. Extremist elements are marginalized through public education efforts and improved monitoring of the political discourse. Top-down attempt at Civic Identity reconstruction. However, the threat of ethnic identity "lock-in" is real as long as powersharing agreement maintains an ethnic or group affiliation as central to political inclusion and avenues of power.

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
The First World Envoy’s decision leads to a military invasion of the capital. The President’s regime is overthrown in a matter of days.

Levels of military violence increase drastically in the short time, but violence against civilians is greatly diminished.

IDP flows are reduced as international peacekeepers subsequently deploy throughout Country X.

The sub-regional rep and first world envoys both engage the remaining government moderates, opposition and insurgent leaders in talks to bring about a new coalition government.

Hardliners in the President’s party are apprehended and detained. They will be brought before an international criminal tribunal to be tried for war crimes, crimes against humanity and genocide.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: Elections

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
The President’s decision to go forward with elections has increased the political rhetoric between various groups within the country as electioneering is in full swing.

Levels of violence associated with the counter-insurgency are steady as opposition leaders maintain pressure in the run-up to elections.

The economy takes a small hit due to uncertainties surrounding the upcoming election. Military elite are closely monitoring the election process to calculate their position in a new government.

Early warning initiatives have paid significant dividends as international media is closely monitoring the political discourse. Weaponry remains a major concern.

fields.name: Short Name
fields.value: start

fields.name: Country Condition
fields.value:
Remnants of the former ruling regime have launched an insurgency in the periphery of the country aimed at destabilizing the new government and forcing new elections.

Government counter-insurgency tactics have taken an anti-Delp character, with international observers accusing the government of genocide. 

National politics are currently conceived as a zero-sum game with economic and security advantages flowing to those linked to the ruling urban elite. 

Presidential elections are constitutionally mandated, but the current government has postponed the next round - set to occur in 3 months time - due to stated security concerns from the ongoing insurgency. 

The current President’s ability to successfully manipulate the insurgency for his own political gain has left many citizens dissatisfied, and he realizes a new round of elections must occur within 6 months.
